## Lists and Tables

### When to Use Lists

**Use numbered lists for:**
- Sequential steps (order matters)
- Ranked items
- Processes with a specific flow

**Use bulleted lists for:**
- Features or characteristics
- Options or alternatives
- Non-sequential items
- 3+ related items that would be awkward as prose

**List best practices:**
- 5-7 items maximum; split longer lists
- Parallel structure (all items start the same way grammatically)
- Don't end list items with periods unless they're complete sentences
- If one item needs explanation, use a description list instead

### When to Use Tables

**Use tables for:**
- Comparing multiple items across the same attributes
- Lookup reference data
- Before/after contrasts
- Feature matrices

**Table best practices:**
- Always include a header row
- Keep tables simple—if you need merged cells, reconsider
- Left-align text, right-align numbers
- Don't use tables for layout—only for actual tabular data
- Add a brief intro sentence before the table

